<div class="body" id="fhbody-176176233">
	
		
	

	
		
		<div id="text-176176233" class="p">
			
		 	
				Connecticut's highest-ranking state legislator has proposed a bill requiring movie theaters to <a href="https://www.registercitizen.com/connecticut/article/ct-movie-theater-start-times-previews-film-looney-20048796.php">disclose both preview and feature film start times</a>, setting up a clash with theater operators who say the measure threatens their advertising revenue.<br> <br>

Senate President Pro Tempore Martin Looney's proposal aims to prevent moviegoers from sitting through up to 30 minutes of advertisements and trailers before features begin. The Democrat cited complaints from constituents about lengthy pre-show delays. Theater owners are pushing back, local outlet RegisterCitizen reports, with Avon Theatre's executive director Peter Gistelinck warning the measure could undermine their financial stability.<br>
		 	
		</div>

		

		

		
			
		
	</div>
